<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=12&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;12</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=14&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;14&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_13.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_13.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>PRE-SPECTRUM</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>12 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
You'll notice that I'm a late-80's Speccy user, and this nostalgic
lookback centres around that period as a result. Sorry about that -
whilst you were probably marvelling at <i>3D Ant Attack</i>, <i>Knightlore</i> and
<i>Monty Mole</i>, I was probably completely unaware of this sort of thing
bar a few games on the school BBC B and a friend's C64.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=200 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d13_watches.png" target="watches.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d13_watches_small.jpg" WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=138></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>When digital watches caught on, suddenly they were given every thinkable feature under the sun - even simple games.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>So what was the Christmas run-up like for the non-Specchum? Life
centred around three things: music on the radio, the Christmas List,
and of course the last day of school in which everybody brought their
toys in to play with whilst eating copious amounts of cakes and
sweets.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/TBXj4BM8RwY&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/TBXj4BM8RwY&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Top Of The Pops Top 40 Xmas 1984</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Because you can never get enough Simon Bates... <b><i>(3:02)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TBXj4BM8RwY" target="TBXj4BM8RwY">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
The early '80s had the music charts in traditional mode - as well as
the usual synth chart fodder, the festive Christmas single was very
much in vogue. Wham may have been teenage pop song after pop song, but
Last Christmas had something special about it that made it stick. Even
the lyrics made some sort of sense. Then there's the ubiquitous Band
Aid single which was very popular in my form because it had "Class 4"
in the lyric "Give to them, there's a class for everyone". Ahem.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The last-day games and the Christmas List eventually rolled into one -
once you tried out a cool game in school, you naturally wanted that
plus ten other games like it. This is where the legendary Argos
catalogue came into its own with page after page of toys, games and
electronic wizardry. Even radios seemed exciting, even though the BBC
stations seemed unappealing to a nine-year-old. However there were the
exciting-sounding "pirate radio stations" Lazer 558 and Caroline
570 which were playing good music, so I used to listen to those on my
new radio. As it turned out they were playing the same music as Radio
1, but the Beeb seemed less exciting to me at the time because, of
course, the same music naturally sounded better broadcasted from a
boat with a low-powered transmitter in the middle of the North Sea.
<TABLE ALIGN="center" WIDTH=379 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d13_hifi1a.jpg" target="hifi1a.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d13_hifi1a_small.jpg" WIDTH=120 HEIGHT=150></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d13_hifi1b.jpg" target="hifi1b.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d13_hifi1b_small.jpg" WIDTH=120 HEIGHT=150></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d13_hifi1c.jpg" target="hifi1c.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d13_hifi1c_small.jpg" WIDTH=119 HEIGHT=150></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=5 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Nice and sharp angles here, but we wanted it all. I loved my portable radio - number 11 on the right.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/2TEHJOwvmvE&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/2TEHJOwvmvE&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Woolworths TV advert from 1983</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">A glorious advert from 1983 showing a cross-section of stuff which would go on people's Christmas lists, including kid's toys and games. <b><i>(1:29)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2TEHJOwvmvE" target="2TEHJOwvmvE">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>

The electronic games revolution was in full swing, and you could opt
to play either chunky "table-top" games to much simpler (yes, hard to
imagine, but this was the early '80s) games on your watch and, for
some bizarre reason, on your calculator. Calculator makers thought
that having simulated rolling dice in their products wasn't enough, so
some of them added musical beeps to the buttons just in case you
fancied rattling off some Rachmaninoff whilst doing your maths
homework. Suddenly LCD displays were appearing everywhere, from
calculator rulers through to pens with digital alarm clocks.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The handheld games were a pure joy, though. A few times every year Mum
would take my brother and I down to London where we'd go into Hamleys
toy shop for an hour or two. An hour or two? Surely we'd get bored?
But no way - there was a full floor in Hamleys filled with counters
covered with as many different types of electronic games as they could
fit in, all powered up, switched on, and inviting players. There was
everything from Speak and Spell through to Munchman, with various
electronic chessboards and space invaders games along the way. All of
them out of my family's budget sadly, but pure heaven to the shiny
novelty-obsessed child from deepest darkest Essex.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Even the board games seemed to be getting more complicated. The Game
of Life kept it simple with a plastic spinning wheel you slotted into
the board which replaced the traditional dice, whereas with Mousetrap
you were effectively building a complex Rube Goldberg machine. Then
cheap plastic moulding came into the equation, allowing for games such
as the marble-preserving Staying Alive and the Pop-o-matic games such
as Frustration whose main selling point was that the dice was encased
in a dome with a spring-loaded floor - and of course that was
irresistible to me.
<TABLE ALIGN="center" WIDTH=374 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d13_prespeccy1a.jpg" target="prespeccy1a.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d13_prespeccy1a_small.jpg" WIDTH=119 HEIGHT=150></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d13_prespeccy1b.jpg" target="prespeccy1b.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d13_prespeccy1b_small.jpg" WIDTH=117 HEIGHT=150></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d13_prespeccy1c.jpg" target="prespeccy1c.jpg"><IMG SRC="pngs/d13_prespeccy1c_small.jpg" WIDTH=118 HEIGHT=150></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=5 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Instant pangs of nostalgia for me here - Hamleys would have all of these and more switched on and ready to play. I can still hum the tune to that BMX game.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
Happy days. Hamleys these days doesn't seem the same without a floor
full of games to play on. With the rise of the consoles, the costs
involved means that there have to be fewer units to play with, and I'm
sure that the last time I had a look around, the console games section
was just a little nook on a single floor.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Sniff... maybe it's time for me to take a little look at eBay before
writing the next entry...
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR><TR><TD><IMG SRC="chocs/voxpop.png" ALIGN="LEFT"><br><IMG SRC="pngs/tomcat.gif" ALIGN="RIGHT"><TABLE BACKGROUND="/black7.png"><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#ffff00"><B><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;TOMAZ KAC&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><br>
<b>RetroSpec have a few legendary remakes under their belts, and their remake of <i>Head Over Heels</i> will retain its classic status for many years to come. Developer Tomaz Kac joins in with our festivities.</b><br><br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Who are you and what are you up to?</font></i></b><br>
I am Tomaz Kac, a software developer in real life and remakes author in spare time.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite cracker gift (aside from fortune-telling fish, naturally)?<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/6hbX_fRgzqk&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/6hbX_fRgzqk&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Santa Claus: The Movie Trailer</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">The "official" Santa Claus movie was just as good as the "official" Santa Claus Spectrum game. <b><i>(2:15)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6hbX_fRgzqk" target="6hbX_fRgzqk">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
</font></i></b><br>
Tickle me Elmo.... :)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Christmas Song?</font></i></b><br>
Nothing beats "The Pogues feat. Kristy Ma - Fairytale of New York" ... that is onehelua xmas song :)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best memory of Christmases gone by?</font></i></b><br>
Getting a Speccy 48k ofcourse... it was not early on though, I had to wait 'til I was 11 or 12. Luckily a neighbour also had one for some months, otherwise I would be playing <i>Thro'the'wall</i> through the whole xmas holidays.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best Speccy Christmas memory?</font></i></b><br>
See previous question :)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Quality Street chocolate?</font></i></b><br>
Kit Kat Chunky. Yeah ! :)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best present ever?</font></i></b><br>
I would say the Speccy, but since my missus will probably see this I would have to go with a great Swatch a few years back. :)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Speccy game you most looked forward to?</font></i></b><br>
<i>Gunfright</i>, definetly... I remember seeing it in the local magazine and I just had to have it. And contrary what many people say, it was GREAT!
